Consider the following policies in a Policy Pack:

```typescript
{
    name: "efs-encrypted",
    description: "Checks whether EFS is configured to encrypt the file data using KMS.",
    config: {
        properties: {
            kmsKeyId: {
                type: "string",
                description: "ARN of the KMS key used to encrypt the EFS file system.",
            },
        },
    },
    validateResource: ...
},
{
    name: "another-policy-name",
    description: "Checks some important things.",
    config: {
        properties: {
            someRequiredProperty: {
                type: "number",
                description: "Some required property.",
            },
        },
        required: ["someRequiredProperty"],
    },
    validateResource: ...
}
```

Each policy in the policy pack has a set of config properties, and each of those config properties has a JSON schema.

Do we send the config schema up as part of each policy's metadata? e.g. add a `ConfigSchema` property to the `apitype.Policy`  struct, something like:

```go
type Policy struct {
	...

	// The JSON schema for the Policy (map of config property name to schema).
	ConfigSchema map[string]PolicyConfigSchema `json:"configSchema,omitempty"`
}


type PolicyConfigSchema struct {
	// Config property name to JSON Schema map.
	Properties: map[string]interface{} `json:"properties,omitempty"`
	// Required config properties.
	Required:   []string               `json:"required,omitempty"`
}
```

Or should the client combine the schemas of all config properties of all policies together into something like the following?

```json
"configSchema": {
    "efs-encrypted": {
        "properties": {
            "kmsKeyId": {
                "type": "string",
                "description": "ARN of the KMS key used to encrypt the EFS file system."
            }
        }
    },
    "another-policy-name": {
        "properties": {
            "someRequiredProperty": {
                "type": "number",
                "description": "Some required property."
            }
        },
        "required": ["someRequiredProperty"]
    }
}
```

In which case, it could be typed as:

```go
type CreatePolicyPackRequest struct {
	...

	// Map of policy name to config schema for the policy.
	ConfigSchema map[string]PolicyConfigSchema `json:"configSchema,omitempty"`
}
```

Or, does the client synthesize a JSON schema for the whole Policy Pack? (Treating the top-level Policy Pack’s schema as an object where each property is a policy name which is an object with each property being the config property.

```json
"configSchema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
        "efs-encrypted": {
            "type": "object",
            "properties": {
                "kmsKeyId": {
                    "type": "string",
                    "description": "ARN of the KMS key used to encrypt the EFS file system."
                }
            }
        },
        "another-policy-name": {
            "type": "object",
            "properties": {
                "someRequiredProperty": {
                    "type": "number",
                    "description": "Some required property."
                }
            },
            "required": ["someRequiredProperty"]
        }
    }
}
```

In which case, it could be typed as `map[string]interface{}` or `interface{}` or `json.RawMessage`:

```go
type CreatePolicyPackRequest struct {
 	// The JSON schema for the Policy Pack's configuration.
 	ConfigSchema map[string]interface{} `json:"configSchema,omitempty"`
}
```

Finally, if we are synthesizing a JSON schema for the whole policy pack, and are allowing the value of each policy name to be either a string `enforcementLevel` or `object` (per my comment [here](https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi/pull/3872/files#r375964463)), do we further synthesize the JSON schema to include that?

```json
"configSchema": {
    "definitions": {
        "enhancementLevel": {
            "type": "string",
            "enum": ["disabled", "advisory", "mandatory"]
        }
    },

    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
        "efs-encrypted": {
            "oneOf": [
                { "$ref": "#/definitions/enhancementLevel" },
                {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "enhancementLevel": { "$ref": "#/definitions/enhancementLevel" },
                        "kmsKeyId": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "ARN of the KMS key used to encrypt the EFS file system."
                        }
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        "another-policy-name": {
            "oneOf": [
                { "$ref": "#/definitions/enhancementLevel" },
                {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "enhancementLevel": { "$ref": "#/definitions/enhancementLevel" },
                        "someConfigurableProperty": {
                            "type": "number",
                            "description": "Some configurable property."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["someConfigurableProperty"]
                }
            ]
        }
    }
}
```

What we decide impacts the DB schema as well.

