What I really like about the code right now is that `updateLineChart` efficiently makes only the necessary changes, and is written in a way such that we might be able to delay/throttle it if we wanted to.

However, some things I found confusing on a first read-through:
- `this.dataExtent` represents the extents of the time series data.  However, it's not updated whenever the series data changes.  Understanding when `this.dataExtent` is up-to-date vs. stale requires knowing how / when `maybeSetViewBoxToDefault` is set.
- If `this.dataExtent` can be stale, does that mean `getDefaultViewBox()`, which depends on it, can be stale as well?  Does this mean `this.viewBox` could be stale?  (as written, I think the PR ensures `this.viewBox` is never stale)
- We are reusing `this.maybeSetViewBoxToDefault` for 2 cases: [view reset on double click] and [view reset due to series data changing while the previous viewBox was equal to the default viewBox]

I'm curious what you think about this proposal:

Perhaps we can replace the `areExtentsEqual(defaultExtent, viewBox)` check entirely with a flag `isViewAtDefault`, and split out a flag `this.shouldResetToDefault` from `this.maybeSetViewBoxToDefault`

```ts
init() {
  this.isViewAtDefault = true;
}

ngOnChanges {
  if (changes['seriesData']) {
    // if view is at default, I care to compute.
    if (this.isViewAtDefault) {
      this.shouldResetToDefault = true;
    }
    // if view is not at default, no need to reset.
  }
}

updateLineChart() {
  if (this.shouldResetToDefault) {
    this.viewBox = this.computeDataSeriesExtent();
    this.shouldResetToDefault = false;
  }
}

onViewBoxChanged(newViewBox) {
  this.isViewAtDefault = false;
  this.shouldResetToDefault = false;
  this.viewBox = newViewBox;
  this.updateLineChart();
}

onViewBoxReset() {
  this.isViewAtDefault = true;
  this.shouldResetToDefault = true;
  this.updateLineChart();
}

```

