@inclement this escaping is the ultimate(TM) shell escaping which should be used *everywhere* - if it was, then we'd have no issue with spaces in folders and all these other things.

It's pretty simple as well, if you think about it: single quotes basically disable everything that could do anything (`$`, space chars, ...) - except for terminating single quotes. So the single quotes themselves are escaped by `'"'"'`, spaced out this is: `'  "  '  "  '`. Explanation: it terminates the current single quote block, then adds a single quote in double escapes (to avoid starting a new block), then starts a new single quote block directly attached.

I got this escaping method from `shlex.quote` actually, I believe?! I forgot. Maybe we could actually use that one, I tend to forget it exists. Anyway, my point was I didn't make this up myself but smarter people did, so the escaping method should be solid :smile:

